Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
2:08pm Court in session

Defendant Nihthanyl Delaney present in court, in custody via video with attorney Larry Pruden. Andrew Herrmann appeared for the State of WIsconsin. 

22CF199
State calls Officer Timothy Swartz, duly sworn & testifies on direct by ADA Herrmann. Officer Swartz identifies the Deft by where he's seated/on the screen & what he's wearing, no objection by Atty Pruden. Record to reflect identification of Deft. 
State introduces previously marked exhibit #1, criminal complaint, into evidence. Atty Pruden would like to ask questions prior to the Court receiving exhibit #1. State objects to questions as to relevance & discovery. Response by Atty Pruden. Court makes record. Atty Pruden does object to the Court receiving exhibit #1 into evidence. Court notes objection but receives exhibit #1 into evidence.
Cross-Exam by Atty Pruden. 
No re-direct by ADA Herrmann. 
No further witnesses on this matter. 

21CF624
State calls Deputy Mitchell Stocking, duly sworn & testifies on direct by ADA Herrmann. Deputy Stocking identifies the Deft by where he's seated/on the screen & what he's wearing, no objection by Atty Pruden. Record to reflect identification of Deft.  
State introduces previously marked exhibit #1, criminal complaint, into evidence. Atty Pruden objects to the Court receiving exhibit #1 & asks questions of the Deputy. ADA Herrmann objects as to relevance. Atty Pruden's response. Court makes record. Atty Pruden objects to the Court receiving exhibit #1 into evidence, further argument. Response by ADA Herrmann. Court receives exhibit #1 into evidence. 
No cross-exam by Atty Pruden. 
No further witnesses. 

Evidence is closed.

Argument by ADA Herrmann
Atty Pruden rests on the record. 

Court finds probable cause that a felony has been committed & that the Deft likely committed it & binds him over to stand trial on both matters. 

State is asking for 30 days for arraignment. 

Atty Pruden asks that these matter move quickly. 
Court notes Atty Pruden's objection however the Statute allows for 30 days.

2:25pm Court in recess
Arraignment scheduled for June 29, 2022 at 01:15 pm.
